{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608737/1958031801/0293.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER FORECAST\nCloudy and cold with occasional light snow\ntoday and tonight, low 32. Cloudy and cold\ntomorrow. (Full report. Page A-2.)\nTemperatures Today\nMidnight 36 6 am... 32 11 a.m....42\n2 a.m.._ .35 8 a.m\u201436 Noon 43\n4am 33 10 am 41 1 pun 44\n106th Year. No. 77.\nCommittee OKs\nPlan to Revise\nMallory Ruling\nBill Prevents Delay\nAfter Arrest From\nBarring Confession\nBy MIRIAM OTTENBERG\nStar Staff Writer\nThe House Judiciary Com\nmittee today approved proposed\nlegislation to remedy the effect\nof the Mallory ruling with a\nnew law.\nCommittee Chairman Celler;\nopposing the proposal himself,\nsaid that the \u201cpreponderant\nmajority\u201d of the full committee\nwas in favor of the recom\nmendation of the subcommittee\nwhich worked on the measure.\nThe bill itself could not be\napproved since it, had not been\nintroduced. It was to be intro\nduced immediately by Subcom\nmittee Chairman Willis, Demo\ncrat of Louisiana, and Repre\nsentative Kramer, Republican\nof Florida, ranking minority\nmember of the subcommittee.\nFormal Action Due\nMr. Celler said the formal ac\ntion on the measure would be\ntaken at the next meeting of\nthe committee.\nThe Supreme Court\u2019s Mallory\ndecision barred a confession at\na rape trial here on the ground\nthat the accused was held too\nlong\u2014seven-and-a-half hours\u2014\nbetween arrest and police ef\nforts to find a committing mag\nistrate.\nThe House Judiciary Sub\ncommittee established to re\nview the impact of several Su\npreme Court decisions last sum\nmer. made the Mallory decision\nits first order of business afld\nheld long hearings.\nContents of Bill\nThe bill finally drafted by the\nsubcommittee and before the\nfull committee today provided\nthat delay alone would not bar\nan otherwise admissible con\nfession. The measure also speci\nfied that law enforcement of\nficers must advise the accused\nthat anything he says may be\nused against him before the\nqu-stioning.\nRepresentative Keating, Re\npublican of New York and\nlinking minority member of\ntha full committee, told re\nporters after the proposal was\napproved today:\n\u201cThis bill will help punish\nthe guilty and protect the in\nnocent. It removes the arti\nficial time barrier set up by\nthe Supreme Court and sub\nstitutes the time-honored test\nof voluntariness as the yard\nstick for measuring the value\nof a confession.\u201d\nThis was the view taken by\nMr. Willis and Mr. Kramer in\npresentirife the subcommittee\nproposal. Both said they felt\nthat the measure achieves a\nbalance between protecting so\nciety and the individual ac\ncused.\nCeller Explains Stand\nChairman Celler told report\ners he had opposed the pro\nposed legislation because it\n\u201cviolates a number of consti\ntutional provisions.\u201d\nWhen staff members ques\ntioned Mr. Celler later about\nthis statement, he said he\nmeant the imposed legislation\n\u201cimpinges\u201d on constitutional\nprovisions andi that he did\nnot mean that the legislation\nwas unconstitutional.\n\u201cIt permits of unlimited de\nlay,\u201d Mr. Celler told reporters.\n\u201cIt puts no limitation on the\ntime between arrest and ar\nraignment and that delay\nwould encourage prosecuting\nofficers to extract confessions\nwith or without coercion, in\ntimidation and promise.\n\u201cThe bill might make easier\nthe task of enforcement officers\nbut I am interested in the in\nnocent whose rights must be\nprotected under the Constitu\ntion\u2014which rights we profess\nSee MALLORY. Page A-6\nFOR\nMORE JOB\nOPPORTUNITIES\np&r I\nSEE\nSTAR\nCLASSIFIED\nIf you are looking for em\nployment or are desirous of\nmaking a change in posi\ntion, be sure to check the\nHelp Wanted columns of\nthe big Star Classified. The\nchances are good you'll find\nJust the spot you\u2019ve been\nlooking for.\nAlways check Star Classi\nfied first for the widest\nvariety of employment op\nportunities Washing\nton's preferred classified\nmedium by more than 2 to\n1 according to an American\nResearch Bureau survey.\n<El)e liicnina\nPhone ST. 3-5000 WASHINGTON, D. C., TUESDAY, MARCH 18, 1958-48 PAGES\nWm\u00dfm HP\nINTRODUCING RRINCE ALBERT\nFour-day-old Prince Albert of Monaco shows little interest in his camera\ndebut with his mother, Princess Grace. Albert is heir to the tiny Medi\nterranean principality now ruled by his father, Prince Rainier. Princess\nGrace is tne former Grace Kelly of Philadelphia and Hollywood.\u2014AP\nWirephoto via radio.\nCity Facing\nLight Snow\nBy Tonight\nWinter dealt Washington an\nother low blow today.\nA light snowfall moved\nj rapidly toward the Na tion\u2019s\nI Capital this afternoon from the\nWest after dropping up to 5\nInches of snow in the Virginia\nmountains and lesser amounts\neverywhere to the west. The\naverage was about 2 inches in\nVirginia and West Virginia.\nAccompanying continued cold\nweather dashed hopes that the\nJapanese cherry blossoms will\nbe in bloom for the festival,\nIMarcn 25 through 30.\nThe eastward-moving snow\nwas reported falling in the\nQuantico and Martinsburg, W.\nVa., areas this afternoon with\nthe Weather Bureau radar\nscope at National Airport show\ning light snow dll around t.he\nsemicircle west of Washington.\nLight Snow Forecast\nThe official forecast was for\noccasional light snow this\nafternoon and early tonight\nwith a low temperature of 32\ndegrees tonight. Tomorrow will\nbe cloudy and continued cold.\n\u201cOnly a miracle can bring\nthe blossoms out In time now.\" j\nsaid Edward J. Kelly, superin-'\ntendent of National Capital;\nParks, the official blossom fore\ncaster.\nHe said the area needs a\nweek of warfh weather with;\ntemperatures in the 70s to\nbring out the pink and white\nblooms. The trees ringing the\nTidal Basin are still in winter\ncondition, he said.\nThe snow and cold won\u2019t hurt\nthe trees \u2014since the buds are\nnot there to be nipped\u2014but the\nlow temperatures will definitely\nretard the blooms.\nToo Late to Alter Plans\nOfficials of the National\nCherry Blossom Festival rue\nfully admitted that the blos\nsom situation looks bad but\nsaid it\u2019s too late to change\nthings now.\n\"It was a calculated risk.\" a\nspokesman said. \u201cWe had to\nmove the fete up because of\nHoly Week, which begins\nMarch 30. We checked records\nfor the last 31 years and found\nthat m 11 of those years the\nblooms were out in the last\nweek of March.\n\"That gave us one chance in\nthree. In the last four years\nthe blooms were out in the\nfirst week of April.\u201d\nPARKING METERS\nBOTHER YOU?\nDON'T TRY THIS\nPlenty of people may\nhave had the urge, but po\nlice said today was the first\ntime they remembered any\none sawing off a downtown\nparking meter.\nIt happened in the 700\nblock of Eighth street N.W.,\napparently moments before\nPvts. Gene J. Bovio and\nBenjamin J. Jastremski of\nthe first precinct arrived in\ntheir police car.\nThe police said they saw\n(l)a parking post with the\nmeter missing, (2) Harry\nEdward Perkins, 22, of\nAlexandria, about to put a\nparking meter into his car\nand (3) a 17-year-old boy\nholding a pipe-cutter.\nPerkins, a sheet-metal\nworker, was charged with\ndestroying District govern\nment property. The boy\nwill face similar charges In\nJuvenile Court.\nHavana Crisis Brings\nBusiness to Standstill\nBatista Answers Demands He Quit\nWith New Plans to Crush Rebels\nHAVANA, Mar. 18 (A I ).\u2014Near paralysis hit many stores\nand businesses in this usually bustling Cuban capital today\nin the wake of demands that President Batista quit to\nend bloodshed.\nGen. Batista answered the demands by calling in his\ntop military and police chiefs to intensify plans for crush-\ning any major rebel attempt to\n(overthrow him.\nHe acted after 42 religious,\nprofessional, fraternal and\nother organizations demanded\nhe get out.\nTheir move came within\nhours after Rebel Leader Fidel\nCastro declared \u201ctotal war.\"\nCastro predicted Gen. Batista\nwould be ousted by a general\nstrike and armed uprising some\ntime in April.\nStreets Nearly Deserted\nStreets usually crowded dur\ning morning shopping hours\nwere nearly deserted. Mer\nchants complained \u201cthere is no\n\u2018business. There is practically\nnobody on the streets and no\nbody is buying anything.\u201d\nInternational airlines re- j\nported some of their planes to\nand from Havana were nearly\nempty. The government quit\nissuing permits for Cubans to\ngo abroad.\nSome American business or\nganizations called off conven\ntions planned for Havana. One 1\nhotel reported four cancella-!\ntions.\n\nMoves Toward Crisis\nTwo star attractions for lux\nury hotels canceled their con\ni tracts. They were the Pianist\nLiberace and Hollywood Singing\nActress Jane Powell. But the'\nnew $24 million, 30-story Ha\nvana Hilton Hotel went ahead\nwith plans for a gala opening\ntomorrow night. Ninety heavily\naimed guards were posted to\nprevent rebel bombing or sabo\ntage attempts. Rebels already\nhave burned rugs In the hotel\u2019s\ngambling casino and hallways.\nCuba apparently was facing\nits most dramatic hour since\nAircraft Cannon Shells\nFall on Three Houses\nSHEBOYGAN PALLS. Wis..\nMar. 18 I/P). \u2014Explosive cannon\nI shells whipped out of the sky\nlast night, pelting streets and\nhammering into at least three\nhouses.\nNo one was Injured, but resi- j\ndents of the area were warned\nto be on the lookout for any\nother shells which might be\nunexploded.\nThe blue-tipped projectiles\nwere identified as shells from\n20-millimeter cannon mounted\non American military aircraft'\nIn Washington, the Air Force\nordered an inspection team to\nSheboygan Falls to make a\ncheck.\nThe Air Force said a B-47\nbomber from Lockbourne Air\nForce Base, near Columbus, I\nOhio, has been identified as\nhaving been in that area about\nthe time of the accident. The\nAir Force has an over-water\npractice filing range alJout 25\nmiles southeast of Sheboygan\nFalls over Lake Michigan.\nThe shells struck shortly!\nafter 7 p.m. in this area, which!\nis about 55 miles north of i\nMilwaukee.\nProjectiles pierced the roofs\nGen. Batista seized power from\nPresident Carlos Prio Socarras\nI in 1952.\nI The nation moved toward a\ncrisis that may only be re\nsolved by widespread bloodshed.\nI; President Batista was deter\nmined to keep power until his\ncandidate, former Premier An-\nI dres Rivero Aguero, is elected\nPresident on June 1.\nThroughout the island rebels\nstepped up bombings, burnings,\nwrecking of comtnunications\nand killings of Batista sup\nporters.\nWarships and planes pa\ntrolled Oriente Province\u2019s coast\nline to prevent landing of re\ninforcements for Castro. Dou-\nSee CUBA, Page A-6\nBritish Disclose\nCrash of Missile\nABERPORTH, Wales, Mar. 18\nUP- \u2014A giant British ground\nto-air guided missile crashed\ni March 6 after being fired from\na testing ground here at Aber\nj porth.\nThe Ministry of Supply said\ntoday the rocket landed on\nwaste ground near a storehouse\nwithout exploding. The missile\ndug a large crater but caused\nno damage.\nI Unofficial reports at this Car\ndigan bay town said that after\nleaving the launching ramp, the\ni missile turned inland instead of\nheading out to sea. Scientists\ncontrolling the launching\ni brought is down by radio.\nBritish scientists make about\n1.000 trial firings each year at\ni Aberporth.\nof the John Novotny house\nhere, the home of Llyod Theune\nat nearby Oostburg and the\nresidence of Francis Deely,\nRoute 2, Sheboygan Falls.\nPolice Chief Henry Dillmann\nof Sheboygan Falls said one\nshell exploded about 20 yards\nahead of his car on Highway\n23 while he was driving between\nSheboygan and Plymouth.\nOfficer Thomas Winter said\nother shells exploded in the\nstreet here.\nUnexploded shells were re\ncovered from the three homes.\nMrs. Novotny said a bullet\nstruck a chest of drawers in the\nsecond-floor bedroom where her\nthree little daughters were\nasleep. The chest stood on the\nspot where the bed had been\nlocated last week before Mrs\nNovotny moved the furniture\nOfficer Winter recovered the\nshell from the Novotny bed\nroom He described it as blue\ntipped. about \"three-quarters of\nan inch in diameter.\" with\nrifling marks near the tail end.\nThe shells which ripped the\njroof at the Theune home\njeaused clothing to catch Are\ni on the second floor, but the fire\nwas extinguished quickly.\nEisenhower to Ask\nTax Cut if Essential\nRebels Reopen\nMedan Battle;\nAmericans Go\nFierce Warriors\nOs Another Province\nJoin Insurgents\nBULLETIN\nSINGAPORE (VP). The\nrebel Padang radio an\nnounced that the town of\nPakanbaru, site of the United\nStates-owned Caltex oil in\nstallations in Central Su\nmatra, was recaptured by\nrebel forces today. There was\nno confirmation from either\nthe Indonesian government\nin Jakarta or revolutionary\nsources here.\nSINGAPORE. Mar. 18 (IP).\u2014\nMilitant Achinese warriors ad\nvanced southward toward dis\nputed Medan in Northern Su\nmatra today and clashed with\ngovernment troops on the city\u2019s\noutskirts.\nThe attack came as 250\nAmericans prepared to evacu-\nPicturc on Page A-3\nate Medan, a city of 300.000,\nwhich Indonesian government\nand rebel forces have been\nfighting for since Sunday.\nThe advance of the Achinese\napparently meant that their\nfierce army of 150,000 war\nriors was allying itself with\nthe rebels. The Achinese, who\nlive in the North Sumatra\nProvince of Atjeh. previously\nhad not entered the fighting.\nAn advance guard converged\non Medan and began sniping\nat government troops. The\nnumber of Achinese and the\nstrength of the government\nforces involved were not\nknown.\nSet Off by Mutiny\nControl of Medan has been\nin doubt since Sunday when\nsome troops mutinied and\nScored a coup against army\nofficers there who have been\nloyal to the Jakarta govern\nment. The government forces\nfought back into control of\nthe city and Maj. Gen. A. H.\nNasution, the army chief of\nstaff, was said to have arrived\nin Medan today.\nThe rebel radio at Bukit\ntinegi reported that the Ja\nkarta commander of Medan,\nLt. Col. Djamin Gintings, who\nretreated with 600 troops into\nthe N mountains during the\nrebel attack Sunday, had re\nturned to Medan to talk to\nGen. Nasution.\nUnited States Vice Consul\nRichard Cleary ordered the 250\nAmericans in the city to leave.\nThey and 825 Dutch Nationals\nplanned to board the liner\nOranje tomorrow for Singa\npore.\nNo Americans Injured\nThe Americans were told to\nleave by United States rubber\nfirms and Christian missions,\nwhose forces make up most of\nthe American population in\nNorth Sumatra. The evacuees\nincluded personnel of the United\nStates Rubber Co. and Good\nyear, which have vast planta\nitions in the areas, and 25\nAmerican missionaries and\nteachers.\nIn a telephone call from\nMedan, Mr. Cleary said no\nAmericans had been injured in\nthe two battles during which\nthe city of 300.000 went into\nrebel hands and back to the\nforces of President Sukarno.\nA battalion of the Medan\ngarrison led by Maj. Boyke\nNainn Golan switched alle\ngiance to the rebel cause Sun\nday and took over the town.\nBut before rebel reinforcements\nfrom *Central Sumatra could\narrive, Mr. Cleary said loyalist\nIndonesian army paratroopers\ndropped on Medan's Belawan\nHarbor early yesterday, then\n'regained control of the city\nafter a brief struggle. Maj.\nNainn Golan and his force\nwithdrew from the city.\nRadio Medan was partly\nknocked out by the fight, but\ntwo of Its four transmitters\nwere operating later.\nWill Buy Soviet Ships\nI Rebel sources in Singapore\nhad reported that Capt. Pohan,\nwho displaced the Jakarta-ap\npointed commander In North\nwest Sumatra\u2019s Tapanuli\nProvince Friday, was advancing\non the Medan with three bat\ntalions. The radio in Padang,\nthe revolutionary government's\nheadquarters on the west coast\nof Central Sumatra, also re\nported that fighting was going\non in the Langkat area north\nof Medan.\nOfficials in Jakarta an\nnounced that the Sukarno gov\nernment has decided to pur\nchase 10 Russian cargo passen\nger ships totaling 23.000 tons.\nFour are already anchored in\n'Jakarta's Tandjong Priok Har\nbor. A contract for two of them\niwas signed Monday.\nVanguard Performance\nExceeded Expectations\nLow Point of 400 Miles Hailed;\nIts Peak May Be 3,000 or Higher\nCAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., Mar. 18 UP.\u2014 Two-actually\nthree\u2014made-in-the-United States moons whizzed around\nthe earth today in company with the sole surviving but al\nready doomed Soviet Sputnik satellite.\nAnd the United States continued to press on with pro\ngrams to launch additional space craft. i\nSputnik II has been given less than a month of remain-\nSputnik II has been given\nless than a month of remaining\nlife.\nThe Navy Vanguard satellite\nwas launched early yesterday\nVanguard Pictures and Related Stories.\nPage A-f\ninto an orbit that pushed new\nfrontiers out into the unknown.\nThe announced orbit ranged\nfrom 400 miles above the earth\nto a peak of 2,500 miles, the\nhighest yet attained by a man\nmade satellite.\nThe Vanguard orbiter repre\nsented not one but two satel\nlites. Its true artificial moon\nwas a shiny aluminum sphere\nonly 6.4 Inches in diameter and\nweighing 3V\u00ab pounds.\nThird Stage Follows\nSomewhere close behind it\nin an 18,000-mile-an-hour orbit\nhundreds oT miles out from the\nearth was the 50-pound, 5-foot- j\nlong, 20 inches wide third-stage;\nrocket that pushed Vanguard\nto orbital speed.\nThe Navy estimated the;\nsphere would stay in orbit 5\nto 10 years. The dead rocket in\nits wake will have a much\nshorter ride.\nSome officials of Martin Co., 1\nwhich built the Vanguard test\nrockets, suggested that tne\norbit peak may be considerably\nabove the 2,500 miles officially\naccorded it, possibly to 3,003\nmiles or higher.\nDr. Milton Rosen, technical\ndirector of the Vanguard proj\nect for the Naval Research\nLaboratory, said the exact\naltitude attained by the new:\nsatellite would not be ascer\ntained until telemetry data and;\nother information received\n2 Witnesses Contfadict\nKatzentine on Pressure\nBy. LEE M. COHN\nand ROBERT K. WALSH\nStar Staff Writers\nHouse investigators ran into\ndirect conflicts of testimony\ntoday, with two witnesses con\ntradicting A. Frank Katzen\ntine\u2019s story of pressure on the\nFederal Communications Com\nmission.\nA third witness. Miami Pub\nlisher John S. Knight, con\nfirmed the substance of Col.\nKatZentine\u2019s testimony before\nthe Legislative Oversight Sub\ncommittee.\nRepresentative O'Hara, Re\npublican of Minnesota, sug\ngested that Col. Katzentine,\nwho lost his bid for television\nchannel 10 in Miami, has \u201ca\nvery good imagination.\" Rep\nresentative Wolverton. Repub\nlican of New Jersey, also ap\npe<\"'ed skentical.\nHarry McDonald, a Washing\nton businessman and former\nchairman of the Securities and\nExchange Commission, denied\nCol. Katzentine* statement\nthat Mr. McDonald had offered\nto intercede with Col. George\nGordon Moore. Mrs. Mamie\nEisenhower\u2019s brother-in-law.\nMoore Denied Charges\nCol. Moore yesterday denied\ncharges that he was \u201cengineer\ning\u201d the channel 10 case for\nNational Airlines, which won\nthe license from the FCC last\nyear.\nAccording to Col. Katzen\nCANINE MYSTERY\nPink Noses Puzzle\nD. C. Dog Doctors\nThe noses of a lot of dogs in\nWashington are turning from\nblack to pink.\nSome of the city's veterinar\nians are concerned, but none\nknows what the cause I*.\nDr. Jean S. Goudy, who has\none of the largest practices in\nthe city, says she has noticed a\ndefinite Increase In pink noses.\nShe said she counted quit'' a\nnumber at the dog show Sun\nday at the National Guard\nArmory.\nShe has also been treating a\nlarge retriever whose nose\nturned pink this winter. Ten\nyears ago she treated a ken\nnelful of Maltese terriers\nwhose noses had gone pink\nbecause of a dietary deficiency.\nShe gave them extra minerals\nin their food and the black\nreturned.\nBut the big retriever is get\nting a proper diet, she said.\nHome Delivered: i&PSSftJJ:* 11 SISS\nfrom the sphere had been\nanalyzed.\nBut Dr. Rosen said he waa\nmore interested in the face\nthat the Vanguard orbit\u2019s low\npoint is 400 miles.\nExceeded Expectations\n\u201cThat\u2019s far better than we\nhad hoped for,\u201d he told a re\nporter. He said provision had\nbeen made for the possibility of\na low point of only 200 miles.\n\"The fact that our low point\nis twice that high means we\nwere much more successful\nthan we had hoped, and that\nthe satellite will have a much\nlonger life than could have\nbpon expected.\u201d he added.\nThe Army launched its Ex\nplorer I satellie January 31.\nThe cylinder is almost seven\nfeet long and six inches in di\nameter. It weighs 30.8 pounds,\nof which only about 12 pqunds\nmake up the instrumented\nsatellite part.\nArmy Secretary Brucker an\nnounced earlier that there may\nbe anqther attempt to launch 1\nan Army satellite within a\nweek.\nIn Washington Dr. John P.\nHagen, director of Project\nVanguard for NRL, said the\nNavy would launch six Van\nguard rockets with 21-inch\n20ti pound spheres and one\nwith a 13-inch plastic lobe.\nSputnik 11, possibly 35 feet\nlong and 5 feet in diameter, is\nexpected to cease orbiting\nabout April 17. The 1,120- i\npound Sputnik has a dead dog;\naboard.\nThe newest United States\nsatellite broadcasts at low pow-\nter on two radio frequencies, 108\nand 108.03 megacycles.\nitine\u2019s previous testimony, Mr.\ni McDonald offered to contact\nCol. Moore's business partner\nand find out whether the\ncharges were true. If they were\ntrue. Col. Katzentine said, Mr.\nMcDonald was to try to \u201cpull\nMoore off.\u201d\nThis version, Mr. McDonald\ntold the subcommittee, was\n\u201cpositively fabricated out of\nnothing.\u201d All he did, he said,\nwas tell Col. Katzentine he\nknew Col. Moore and his part\nner.\nBut Mr. McDonald acknowl\nedged he did pass on to Col.\nKatzentine \u201cscuttlebutt\u201d picked\nup from Robert Jones, a former\nFCC chairman and a lawyer for\none of the four applicants in\nthe Miami TV case.\nReopening Reported\nMr. Jones told him, Mr. Mc-\nDonald recalled, that the FCC\nprobably would reopen the case\ninstead of awarding the chan\nnel to any of the four appli\ncants.\nMr. Knight, who publishes\nthe Miami Herald and other\nnewspapers, testified that Alex\nander Hardy, vice president of\nNational Airlines, was \u201cex\ntremely confident\u201d of winning\nChannel 10 and \u201cfelt he had\nthree votes.\u201d\nCol. Katzentine has testified\nthat Mr. Knight told him of\na conversation with Mr. Hardy.\nContinued on Page A-7, Col. 1\nDr. Goudy doesn\u2019t know what\nIs wrong with his nose, unless\nIt is a \u201cmetabolic disorder.\"\nDr. H. Carlton Newman,\npresident of the District Acad\nemy of Veterinary Medicine,\nsaid today that pink nose is\nnot a great rarity. He said the\ncondition is sometimes called\n\u201csnow nose,\" because lt occurs\nfrequently among sled dogs in\nthe Far North. A theory is\nthat strong sunlight, reflected\noff the snow, causes the nose\nto turn pink\nDr. Erven Ross, however, said\nthat in his practice pink nose\nhas shown up more often\namong dogs which are kept in\ndoors a lot. He said he had not\nnoticed any particular increase\nj this year.\nDr. William C. Ready theor\nized that pink nose may be seen\nmore often these days simply\nbecause there are more dogs.\nMetropolitan\nEdition\nNew York Markets, Poga A-17\nWon't Bow\nTo Panic, He\nTells Women\nPresident Eisenhower prom\nised today to push any action,\nincluding tax reduction, if that\nshould prove necessary, that\nwill \u201cassist healthy economic\nrecovery.\u201d\nBut the President emphasized\nthat his administration \"is not\nVictory in 'SB Colled Key to Presi\ndency. Page 1-4\nHighlights of President's Talk to\nG. O. P. Women. Page A-6\ngoing to be panicked by alarm\nists into activities\" that could\nmake present economic hard\nships more prolonged.\nMr. Eisenhower reviewed\nsteps taken to combat the re\ncession and promised future\naction as needed in a speech to\nthe Republican women\u2019s an\nnual national conference at the\nStatler Hotel this afternoon.\nHe also lashed out at a Sen\nate-passed bill freezing farm\nprice supports as \u201ca 180-degree\nturn in the wrong direction\u201d\nthat could lead only to \u201cper\npetual troubles for the farmer.\"\nOn \u2022other subjects, the Prest\ndent:\n1. Called for \u201cprompt, de\ncisive and fair corrective ac\nj tion\u201d to weed out any Govern\nment officials debating from\nhigh standards of official con\n-1 duct.\n2. Described foreign aid and\nextension of the Reciprocal\nTrade Agreements Act, with\nliberalized tariff-cutting pro\nvisions, as \u201cindispensable build\ning stones\u201d in the struggle to\nachieve the kind of world\nAmerica wants.\n3. Called for both political\nparties to \u201cstand up and be\ncounted\u201d as dedicated to the\nbest interests of the Nation and\nthe world, declaring that Amer\ni ica now cannot tolerate dema\ngoguery In any individual or in\nany party that \"would put win\nning a cheap political advan\ntage above winning the world\nstruggle for justice and free\ndom.\u201d\nConfident on Recovery\nMr. Eisenhower expressed\nunqualified confidence in Amer\nica\u2019s recovery from the current\nrecession.\n\u201cThis recovery effort of the\nAmerican people will be suc\ncessful,\u201d he declared. \u201cWe know\nit will be successful, because we\nhave faith in our Nation, in\nour free economy and in our\nselves.\u201d\nHe emphasized that the Re\npublican Party\u2019s guiding prin\nciple in regard to the economy\nis to be prepared whenever\nnecessary to do whatever it can\ntb help bring about a healthy\nincrease in employment and\nbusiness activity. But he added\nthat \u201cthe real mainspring of\nour kind of economy is not\ngovernment, but the built-in\nthrust and vigor of private en\nterprise.\u201d\nMr. Eisenhower mentioned\nthe possibility of a tax cut to\nhelp combat the recession only\nin passing.\nHe spoke after some confu\nsion had arisen over the extent\nto which tax cut possibilities\nwere discussed at a meeting of\nSee ECONOMIC. Page A-8\nStocks Register\nGeneral Decline\nNEW YORK, Mar. 18 UP\nThe stock market fell back a\nfew cents to about $2 a share\nin a general retreat today. It\ncontinued a decline which got\nunder way yesterday.\nMost sections of the list were\naffected by the selling with air\ncrafts, steels and metals under\nmajor pressure.\nConcern over the businest\nsituation was offered by broker*\nas the reason for the downturn.\nOLD FISHERMAN\nSEEKS BOAT LAWS\nTHE AUTHOR of the tanner bill\nto regulate pleasure craft is en eld\nhand at boating and fishing. For a\nbackground on the North Caroline\nRepresented** see Charles Cavell'l\ncolumn an The Leisure Sportsman\nRage, A-23.\nIREADIAKING\u2014a lost art among\nhousewives\u2014is made easy with la\nday's prepared dough miies says\nThe Star's food editor, Violet Faulk\nner, en Page 8-9.\nGuide for Readers\nAmuse'ts A-14-15, Feature Page 8-19\nBusiness end Leisura Sp'rts A-23\nFmance A-16-17 Music A 14\nClassified 8-13-18 Obituary 8-12\nComics 8-21-23 Sports A-l* 23\nCrossword 8-22 TV-Radio 8-20\nEditoriol A-12 j Woman's\nEdit'l Articles A-13 Section 8-4-10\nHave The Stor Delivered to\nI Your Home Daily and Sunday\nDial STerling 3 5000\n5 CENTS","height":"28676","width":"18348"}}
